# What Docker Alone Doesn't Solve

You can `docker compose` a small stack. The gap opens with **many machines + many apps**.

## The six problems Kubernetes owns

- **Placement** — which container on which node? The **scheduler**.
- **Self-healing** — container or node dies → replaced.
- **Scaling** — set `replicas: 10`; the cluster converges.
- **Rollouts** — start v2, verify, stop v1; one-command rollback.
- **Service discovery** — a stable **Service** name, not pod IPs.
- **Config & secrets** — first-class **ConfigMaps** / **Secrets**.

> **Docker** (a runtime) still does the container work; **Kubernetes** sits on top — placing, healing, scaling. The moment you have **more containers than you can supervise**, you want an orchestrator.
